[normal]http://www.bbc.co.uk/aboutthebbc/insidethebbc/whoweare/wherenext/
[normal]?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As a mere member of the public it is often hard to keep up, much less stay on top of it all. But as one taking
[normal] a big interest in the national broadcaster that claims to speak for me, more often at me, when an opportunity to speak back comes, especially out of their often less than trustworthy controls, it needs to be grasped.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]One recognizes there’s a danger such 
[normal]interest and challenge sees key issues get lost in the attrition of vast volumes of testimony and data.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]But these are all not appearing by mere coincidence. There has been for too long something very rotten at the heart of the BBC, and despite great claim
[normal]s, there are some (even those well entrenched and often with the empathy of familiarity) with reduced confidence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The committee will be getting many submissions of detail into BBC failures of bias and impartiality as broadcasters, plus eye-watering waste 
[normal]and inefficiency as a public-sector ‘business’. I will add a few lowlights of my own. But for a neat summary you could do worse than these on who there spends what money how well:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2515367/LITTLEJOHN-And-BBC--1bn-wasted.html
