[normal]3.2 Here’s a recent review by Open Democracy. They post infrequently, and often err on the ‘understanding’ of the BBC’s mission and issues, but 
[normal]can
[normal] delve deeply, so this one was a novel detailed critique to see:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://www.opendemocracy.net/ourbeeb/lis-howell/tony-halls-speech-didnt-answer
[normal]-any-of-real-questions
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The whole point to any BBC supposed response and… what often seems an attitude from top down epitomized by the Trust Chair: ‘the BBC only asks questions and does not answer them’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]’I don’t think James Purnell really answered the
[normal] points I made. These weren’t debating points or arguments about stance or even about policy. There were things I wanted to know – practical factual things which I wanted Tony Hall to tell me.‘
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]’If your pension or your salary comes via investments in ITV 
[normal]or Sky, or any other media organisation which isn’t subsidised by the licence fee, you have every right to be alarmed by the BBC using your licence fee money to undercut the commercial organisations which pay you. This was an issue which was supposed to be
[normal] dealt with by the BBC Trust,’
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC is non-commercial, obviously. But it seems to exist, and is uniquely funded, to crush opposition. Overseen by that ill-named Trust. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]’it seems highly likely that there will be fewer licence fee payers in the future,
[normal] even though one-person-homes have increased. So the money just isn’t going to be there’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Unless, of course, those who have hacked away at critics online and print (the Times? Since when?) get their ways to seeing a propaganda and censorship-guided, state
[normal]-enforced imposition of a fee that any PC or internet connection requires a BBC tithe too? That is, of course, a question. As is this…
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]’Do Tony and James really understand the vast numbers of well-informed people with hugely differing demands out there?’
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC won’t, or will try and get it lost in a sea of attrition, so I’ll offer a definitive answer: No.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]But that won’t stop them doing all in their power to ensure such people are isolated, mocked, twitter-hounded and crushed in having any say, or influ
[normal]ence on a majority of sofa-bound UK public who get their information, in, out or ‘enhanced’ via the BBC edit suite’s highly unique filter.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]You can’t tell everyone how much you are trusted or transparent you are, when you’re not, without learning a few les
[normal]sons from history. Some treasures may end up better buried.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3 Here’s another telling comment from a hardly critical source about the BBC, claims, ‘sources who say’, and what they expect of others but wouldn’t dream of applying to themselves:
