[normal]4.7[bold] And when faced with such questions, what they actually do is procrastinate, prevaricate and in e
[normal]xtreme cases lash out in total abuse of their authority. I am currently ‘banned’, meaning they don’t feel they need look at respond to any concerns I raise. Why?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]More critically, what gives the BBC the right and authority to [bold]investigate me[bold] using what is in effect private detectives, simply to silence a critic?[bold]I made a complaint (around May 2012) to the BBC via its online portal. They responded by claiming they are banning me from pointing out their inaccuracies and unprofessionalism based 
[normal]not on merit of complaint, but on the number of times I catch them out. More crucially, they dredge up ‘alleged’ evidence, and to date umproven, based on what appears to be a concerted effort to search the entire global internet for commenters who are crit
[normal]cial about the BBC and may be me. Or at least close enough for their purposes.
[normal]I demanded to know what they are playing at making searches across the internet and social media even attempting, but failing to prove any linkages between me the complainant an
[normal]d any critics they may be obsessing about in service of internal grievances. Far from providing any explanation, they initiate a vast, several month long multi-£ ‘investigation’ into the ‘case’, but actually more on me, 
[normal]dragging in outside investigators[bold] to
[normal] further share in/enhance the information held.
[normal]The ‘investigation’ and ‘evidence’ is held in camera, and anonymously within the BBC at all times, with no opportunity for challenge or clarification. The right to question or challenge is routinely ignored.
[normal]The BBC Trust arbitrates upon this, and dismisses any concerns on such extra-BBC activity as a matter of ‘belief’ the BBC has nothing to answer for. I beg to differ. The ICO also has now expressed interest.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.8 The BBC 'Trust' Star Chamber of course meets
[normal] in secret, and only interviews un-named BBC-selected witnesses and/or experts behind doors closed to the public. What they see and hear is therefore anyone's guess. This is a key part of their steamroller unaccountability (of course such as previous DG's,
[normal] Nick Pollard, etc, have discovered/claimed that they can't be held to account because mystery underlings have kept them out of such loops... another Beware of the Leopard implausible deniability creation of theirs for just such a reason). At the start Pol
[normal]lard was mentioned, not in a good way. Now, it is back again, and in light of what is raised here, in even less good a way.
